SIMPLE: enamel
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enamel
<hw>En*am"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>en-</ets>
+ <ets>amel</ets>. See <er>Amel</er>, <er>Smelt</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A variety of glass, used in ornament,
to cover a surface, as of metal or pottery, and admitting of after
decoration in color, or used itself for inlaying or application in
varied colors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A glassy, opaque bead obtained by
the blowpipe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is enameled; also, any smooth, glossy
surface, resembling enamel, especially if variegated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The intensely hard calcified
tissue entering into the composition of teeth. It merely covers the
exposed parts of the teeth of man, but in many animals is intermixed in
various ways with the dentine and cement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any one of various preparations for giving a smooth,
glossy surface like that of enamel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A cosmetic intended to give the appearance of a
smooth and beautiful complexion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Enamel painting</b></col>, <cd>painting with enamel
colors upon a ground of metal, porcelain, or the like, the colors being
afterwards fixed by fire.</cd> -- <col><b>Enamel paper</b></col>,
<cd>paper glazed a metallic coating.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enamel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Enamel
<hw>En*am"el</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Enameled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Enamelled</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Enameling</conjf> or
<conjf>Enamelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lay enamel
upon; to decorate with enamel whether inlaid or painted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 488 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To variegate with colors as if with
enamel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Oft he [the serpent]bowed⟦br⟧
His turret crest and sleek <qex>enameled</qex> neck.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To form a glossy surface like enamel upon; <as>as,
to <ex>enamel</ex> card paper; to <ex>enamel</ex> leather or
cloth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To disguise with cosmetics, as a woman's
complexion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enamel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Enamel
<hw>En*am"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To practice the
art of enameling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enamel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Enamel
<hw>En*am"el</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Relating to the art of enameling;
<as>as, <ex>enamel</ex> painting</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Tomlinson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enamelar</ent>⟦br⟧
